      {
        "id": "presentation-guide",
        "title": "Presentation Guide",
        "scrollable": true,
        "root": [
          {
            "tag": "h1",
            "attributes": {
              "class": "text-4xl font-bold text-indigo-700 text-center"
            },
            "children": [{ "text": "Multiple Intelligence Theory" }]
          },
          {
            "tag": "h1",
            "attributes": {
              "class": "text-4xl font-bold text-indigo-700 mb-6 text-center"
            },
            "children": [{ "text": "Lesson 8: Presentation" }]
          },
          {
            "tag": "h3",
            "attributes": { "class": "text-2xl font-bold text-blue-600" },
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "SAMPLE OUTLINE FOR PRESENTATION: “MULTIPLE INTELLIGENCES”"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "This is a sample outline for your presentation about "
              },
              {
                "tag": "strong",
                "children": [{ "text": "Multiple Intelligences" }]
              },
              {
                "text": ". You can use it as a model or make changes to create your own version. The outline includes both the "
              },
              { "tag": "strong", "children": [{ "text": "onscreen content" }] },
              { "text": " (what appears on the slide) and the " },
              { "tag": "strong", "children": [{ "text": "speaker script" }] },
              { "text": " (what you say during your presentation)." }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "h4",
            "attributes": {
              "class": "text-xl font-semibold text-blue-600 pt-2"
            },
            "children": [{ "text": "1. Understanding the Goal" }]
          },
          { "tag": "p", "children": [{ "text": "This presentation will:" }] },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Explain Howard Gardner’s Multiple Intelligence theory clearly."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Describe each type of intelligence with examples."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  { "text": "Discuss its implications for education." }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Connect the theory to your own learning style and experiences."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "h4",
            "attributes": {
              "class": "text-xl font-semibold text-blue-600 pt-2"
            },
            "children": [
              { "text": "2. Presentation Structure (Slides Overview)" }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "h5",
            "attributes": { "class": "text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600" },
            "children": [{ "text": "Introduction (Slides 1–3)" }]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Introduce the topic and background of intelligence measurement."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "tag": "span",
                    "children": [
                      {
                        "tag": "strong",
                        "children": [{ "text": "Talk about:" }]
                      },
                      { "text": " Alfred Binet’s IQ test and its limits." }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "tag": "span",
                    "children": [
                      {
                        "tag": "strong",
                        "children": [{ "text": "Talk about:" }]
                      },
                      {
                        "text": " Howard Gardner and the idea of Multiple Intelligences."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "tag": "span",
                    "children": [
                      {
                        "tag": "strong",
                        "children": [{ "text": "Script example:" }]
                      },
                      {
                        "text": " “In the early 20th century, intelligence was measured mainly by IQ. But later, Howard Gardner from Harvard suggested that people are smart in many different ways.”"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "h5",
            "attributes": {
              "class": "text-xl font-semibold text-blue-600 mt-4"
            },
            "children": [
              { "text": "Main Content – Types of Intelligence (Slides 4–13)" }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Describe each intelligence type. Keep each slide focused on one type only."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "strong",
                "children": [{ "text": "a. Linguistic Intelligence" }]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "tag": "span",
                    "children": [
                      {
                        "tag": "strong",
                        "children": [{ "text": "Talk about:" }]
                      },
                      {
                        "text": " reading, writing, speaking, learning languages."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "tag": "span",
                    "children": [
                      { "tag": "strong", "children": [{ "text": "Script:" }] },
                      {
                        "text": " “People with strong linguistic intelligence enjoy reading and communicating. They can develop it by reading books and joining discussions.”"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "strong",
                "children": [{ "text": "b. Logical–Mathematical Intelligence" }]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: working with numbers, solving problems, finding patterns."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script: “Logical thinkers enjoy puzzles and problem-solving. They are good at reasoning and analyzing information.”"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "strong",
                "children": [{ "text": "c. Musical Intelligence" }]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  { "text": "Talk about: rhythm, sound, music creation." }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script: “People with musical intelligence recognize rhythm and melody easily. They learn through music, singing, or playing instruments.”"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "strong",
                "children": [{ "text": "d. Spatial Intelligence" }]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: visual imagination, drawing, directions."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script: “Spatial learners think in pictures. They are good at design, art, and visualizing things in space.”"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "strong",
                "children": [{ "text": "e. Bodily-Kinesthetic Intelligence" }]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: movement, hands-on activities, expressing through body."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script: “These learners use their bodies to express ideas. They learn best through physical activities or role-playing.”"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "strong",
                "children": [{ "text": "f. Interpersonal Intelligence" }]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: teamwork, understanding others, communication."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script: “Interpersonal learners are good at understanding others and working in teams. They enjoy discussions and group projects.”"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "strong",
                "children": [{ "text": "g. Intrapersonal Intelligence" }]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: self-awareness, emotions, reflection."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script: “Intrapersonal learners understand their feelings and motivations. They prefer studying alone and reflecting on their thoughts.”"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "p",
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "strong",
                "children": [{ "text": "h. Naturalist Intelligence" }]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  { "text": "Talk about: nature, animals, environment." }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script: “Naturalist learners are connected to nature. They learn by exploring, observing, and discovering the environment.”"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "h5",
            "attributes": {
              "class": "text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mt-4"
            },
            "children": [{ "text": "Educational Implications (Slides 14–15)" }]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  { "text": "Talk about: how MI theory affects classrooms." }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script: “Teachers should use varied methods — reading, teamwork, problem-solving, and creative tasks — to help all types of learners.”"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: recognizing strengths, avoiding one-size-fits-all teaching."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "h5",
            "attributes": {
              "class": "text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mt-4"
            },
            "children": [{ "text": "Personal Reflection (Slides 16–17)" }]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: your strongest and weakest intelligences."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script example: “My strongest intelligences are linguistic and interpersonal. I love communicating with people and sharing ideas. My weakest one is logical, so I try to practice problem-solving more often.”"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: how you use your strengths and improve weaker areas."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "tag": "h5",
            "attributes": {
              "class": "text-lg font-semibold text-blue-600 mt-4"
            },
            "children": [{ "text": "Conclusion (Slides 18–20)" }]
          },
          {
            "tag": "ul",
            "attributes": { "class": "list-inside ml-6 space-y-1" },
            "children": [
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: the idea that intelligence is not fixed."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Script: “In conclusion, intelligence comes in many forms. Every person has different strengths that can be developed. Education should support every learner’s unique way of thinking.”"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "tag": "li",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Talk about: thanking the audience and acknowledging sources."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "containerClassName": "bg-white bg-opacity-90 rounded-xl p-10 shadow-2xl text-xl"
      }
    ]
  }
